VII. These seas do not contain very many islands. ᾒῑαέἆψίῖ The most famous is Zerba, 25 miles long and 22 miles ‘ s rrrrr broad, called by Eratosthenes Lotus Eaters’ Island. It has two towns, Meninx on the side of Africa and Thoar on the other side, the island itself lying off the promontory on the right-hand side of the Lesser Syrtis, at a distance of a mile and a half away. A hundred miles from Zerba and lying off the left- hand promontory is the island of Cercina, with the free city of the same name3 it is 25 miles long and measures half that distance across where it is widest, but not more than 5 miles across at its end3 and joined to it by a bridge is the extremely small island os Cercinitis, which looks towards Carthago. About 50 miles from these is Lopadusa, 6 miles long3 then come Gaulos and Galata, the soil of the latter having the property of killing scorpions, that pest of Africa. It is also said that scorpions cannot live at Clupea, opposite to which lies Pantellaria with its town. Opposite the Gulf of Carthage lie the two Aegi- moeroi; but the Altars, which arc more truly rocks than islands, are chiefly between Sicily and Sar- dinia. Some authorities state that even the Altars were formerly inhabitcd but that their level has sunk.
